<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="570" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1869,2038]" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,419,1869,1894]" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">Diagnosis of male.</emphasis>
Dorsal surface of head and pronotum finely punctate, tergite IV with sparse and shallow punctures; antennomeres subcylindrical; elytra with shallow sutural and discal striae; protibiae with small apical bunch of setae; tergite IV modified, with a distinct triangular tubercle at posterior portion, and two much smaller tubercles lateral to tubercle; aedeagus with suberect, and markedly elongate ventral and dorsal lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="571" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1869,2038]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1437,151,717]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="571" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,2013,2038]" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">Description.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[430,501,2013,2038]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1741,1763]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,558,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,558,1717]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Diagnostic features of Batriscenellus pengzhongi. A. Male habitus (with apex of right protibia enlarged); B. Head dorsum and pronotum; C. Abdominal tergites IV – VII, in dorsal view; D – E. Aedeagus, in lateral (D) and ventral (E) views. Scale bars: 0.5 mm in A; 0.2 mm in B – C; 0.1 mm in D – E." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887878/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="570">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
A). Body reddish-brown, length 
<quantity box="[879,1049,2014,2038]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.21" metricValueMax="2.24" metricValueMin="2.18" pageId="9" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="2.21" valueMax="2.24" valueMin="2.18">2.18–2.24 mm</quantity>
. Head subrectangular, wider than long, HL 
<quantity box="[258,423,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.15" metricValueMax="4.3" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="571" unit="mm" value="0.415" valueMax="0.43" valueMin="0.4">0.40–0.43 mm</quantity>
, HW 
<quantity box="[488,652,151,176]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.15" metricValueMax="5.2" metricValueMin="5.1" pageId="10" pageNumber="571" unit="mm" value="0.515" valueMax="0.52" valueMin="0.51">0.51–0.52 mm</quantity>
, dorsal surface finely punctate (
<figureCitation box="[1008,1075,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1741,1763]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,558,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,558,1717]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Diagnostic features of Batriscenellus pengzhongi. A. Male habitus (with apex of right protibia enlarged); B. Head dorsum and pronotum; C. Abdominal tergites IV – VII, in dorsal view; D – E. Aedeagus, in lateral (D) and ventral (E) views. Scale bars: 0.5 mm in A; 0.2 mm in B – C; 0.1 mm in D – E." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887878/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="571">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
B); vertex lacking median ridge, U-shaped sulcus only indicated at anterior margin; antennomeres subcylindrical, clubs formed by apical three antennomeres; each eye composed of about 30 facets. Pronotum about as long as wide, PL 
<quantity box="[1212,1380,224,248]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.85" metricValueMax="4.9" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="571" unit="mm" value="0.485" valueMax="0.49" valueMin="0.48">0.48–0.49 mm</quantity>
, PW 
<quantity box="[151,314,260,285]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.9" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="571" unit="mm" value="0.49" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.48">0.48–0.50 mm</quantity>
finely punctate (
<figureCitation box="[505,573,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1741,1763]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,558,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,558,1717]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Diagnostic features of Batriscenellus pengzhongi. A. Male habitus (with apex of right protibia enlarged); B. Head dorsum and pronotum; C. Abdominal tergites IV – VII, in dorsal view; D – E. Aedeagus, in lateral (D) and ventral (E) views. Scale bars: 0.5 mm in A; 0.2 mm in B – C; 0.1 mm in D – E." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887878/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="571">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
B). Elytra wider than long, EL 
<quantity box="[924,1089,260,285]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="7.6" metricValueMin="7.4" pageId="10" pageNumber="571" unit="mm" value="0.75" valueMax="0.76" valueMin="0.74">0.74–0.76 mm</quantity>
, EW 
<quantity box="[1153,1318,260,284]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.25" metricValueMax="8.299999999999999" metricValueMin="8.2" pageId="10" pageNumber="571" unit="mm" value="0.825" valueMax="0.83" valueMin="0.82">0.82–0.83 mm</quantity>
, narrowed at base, shallow discal striae extending to apical 2/3 of elytral length; sutural striae complete. Protibiae with small apical bunch of setae. Abdomen wider than long, AL 
<quantity box="[755,920,332,356]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.85" metricValueMax="4.9" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="571" unit="mm" value="0.485" valueMax="0.49" valueMin="0.48">0.48–0.49 mm</quantity>
, AW 
<quantity box="[984,1149,332,357]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.9" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="571" unit="mm" value="0.49" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.48">0.48–0.50 mm</quantity>
, tergite IV (
<figureCitation box="[1285,1351,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1741,1763]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,558,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,558,1717]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Diagnostic features of Batriscenellus pengzhongi. A. Male habitus (with apex of right protibia enlarged); B. Head dorsum and pronotum; C. Abdominal tergites IV – VII, in dorsal view; D – E. Aedeagus, in lateral (D) and ventral (E) views. Scale bars: 0.5 mm in A; 0.2 mm in B – C; 0.1 mm in D – E." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887878/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="571">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
C) with sparse and shallow punctures, with distinct triangular tubercle at posteromedian portion, and two much smaller tubercles lateral to tubercle. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[599,665,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1741,1763]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,558,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,558,1717]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Diagnostic features of Batriscenellus pengzhongi. A. Male habitus (with apex of right protibia enlarged); B. Head dorsum and pronotum; C. Abdominal tergites IV – VII, in dorsal view; D – E. Aedeagus, in lateral (D) and ventral (E) views. Scale bars: 0.5 mm in A; 0.2 mm in B – C; 0.1 mm in D – E." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887878/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="571">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
D–E) strongly asymmetric, length 
<quantity box="[1058,1160,404,428]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="571" unit="mm" value="0.38">0.38 mm</quantity>
, with elongate and erect ventral and dorsal lobes, ventral lobe laterally projecting near middle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,717]" box="[199,413,476,501]" pageId="10" pageNumber="571">Female. Unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="10" pageNumber="571">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,439,511,536]" pageId="10" pageNumber="571">Comparative Notes.</emphasis>
At present, this new species cannot be placed in any known species groups within the genus. The unique presence of a distinct triangular tubercle on the posteromedian portion of male tergite IV, and the elongate and erect aedeagal ventral and dorsal lobes quickly separate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yin" authorityYear="2017" box="[997,1165,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Batriscenellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="571" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pengzhongi">
<emphasis box="[997,1014,585,608]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="571">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1036,1165,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="571">pengzhongi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all other known congeners.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
